# Milestone 2: Transition from RViz to Gazebo

After validating the robot geometry and kinematic chain in RViz, the model was transferred to Gazebo 11 to introduce physics-based simulation.

RViz is primarily used for robot visualization and transform verification, while Gazebo simulates physical behavior such as gravity, inertia, 
contact, collision, and joint dynamics.

## Gazebo Integration Work

The following changes were required to make the RViz model operate correctly in Gazebo:

- Created a Gazebo launch file to start the simulator and spawn the URDF model.
- Added physical properties to the robot links.
- Added nonzero mass and inertia values for all physical links.
- Added damping and friction to the revolute joints.
- Fixed the robot base to the simulation world.
- Corrected the complete robot orientation relative to the Gazebo ground plane.
- Adjusted the robot spawn position so the base rests correctly on the ground.
- Disabled or simplified unstable collision meshes during initial testing.
- Added simplified collision geometry where physical contact was required.
- Verified that the robot remains stable under Gazebo physics.
- Confirmed that the links remain connected and no longer shake under gravity.

